<para id="fs-idm343994800">President John F. Kennedyâ€™s inaugural address on January 20, 1961, remains one of the most widely recognized examples of presidential oratory. Kennedyâ€™s speech was brief and thematic, using paradoxical turns of phrase that suggested poignancy and a new perspective on the meaning of political participation. Several phrases that appeared in the address entered into the national vocabulary. The speechâ€™s main points were to encourage public service and provide an expansive foreign policy vision for Cold War America.</para>
<para id="fs-idm327587312">Kennedy began preparing his inaugural address in earnest in the closing weeks of his transition into office, in early January 1961. He asked his confidant and advisor, Theodore Sorensen, to help him draft it. The president-elect was aware that his victory in the 1960 election the previous November had been narrow (the popular-vote margin was two-tenths of 1 percent) and that his campaign had been characterized by generalities rather than specifics. However, he opted to prepare an inaugural address that would continue to appeal to general principles rather than specific policies. He also wanted to look to the future with hope and optimism for a rising generation of Americans. He asked Sorensen whether he could identity the â€œsecretâ€ of Lincolnâ€™s Gettysburg Address and draft a speech draft with that in mind.</para>
<para id="fs-idm519789744">Sorensen concluded that an important characteristic of Lincolnâ€™s address was the preference for small words and short phrases that could capture a point more profoundly than long, wordy passages. Kennedy said he wanted his address to be one of the briefest of presidential inaugurals, and he wanted it to give foreign policy precedence over domestic policy on the grounds that the nation could unify on the Cold War outlook in foreign affairs but was necessarily divided about political issues at home.</para>
<para id="fs-idm660764080">Sorenson completed a draft in early January that was fewer than 1,900 words. He had studied the vast record of Kennedyâ€™s political speeches (Kennedy had given upward of 15 speeches a day while running for president) and identified material that would suit the inaugural. Sorensenâ€™s work was largely a collection of lines Kennedy had already voiced on the campaign trail in 1960 or during his career in the Senate since 1953, adjusted to meet the circumstances of the beginning of his presidency. Kennedy worked on Sorensenâ€™s draft extensively in the two weeks before the inaugural, mainly at his fatherâ€™s home in Palm Beach, Florida, refining it into the finished product that became the inaugural address of January 20.</para>
<para id="fs-idm512767680">Whether Sorensen or Kennedy principally wrote the inaugural address has long been an issue of historical debate, stemming from questions that had arisen in 1957 when Kennedyâ€™s book <emphasis effect="italics">Profiles in Courage</emphasis> won the Pulitzer Prize. Critics claimed that Sorensen had substantially written that book. In response, Kennedy successfully pressured news organizations to retract such claims or face a lawsuit. The balance of the evidence today indicates that Kennedy was largely the author of his book and his inaugural address. The ideas and language originated with Kennedy, and Sorensen (<link target-id="BRI_APUSH_14_03_Sorensen"/>) collaborated on the writing.</para>
<figure id="BRI_APUSH_14_03_Sorensen" class="scaled-down-30">
<media id="fs-idm471098944" alt="Theodore Sorensen reads a document at his desk.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/BRI_APUSH_14_03_Sorensen.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption>Theodore Sorensen was a close confidant of President Kennedy and later served as special counsel to the president after the inauguration.</caption>
</figure>
<para id="fs-idm386628624">Kennedyâ€™s inauguration day followed a night of elegant parties in Washington, DC, as well as a violent snowstorm. The parade preceding the ceremony was in doubt until an army of workers removed the many cars on Pennsylvania Avenue that had been buried in the snow. Robert Frost was supposed to read a poem he had written for the occasion, but the sun was so brilliant that he could not read his script. Instead, he recited from memory another poem, â€œThe Gift Outright,â€ a song to the settlement of the United States that he had composed in 1941.</para>
<para id="fs-idm336372000">Immediately after taking the oath of office at midday, Kennedy delivered his address, hatless and without an overcoat in 20Â°F weather (<link target-id="BRI_APUSH_14_03_KennedyIna"/>). After brief opening pleasantries, the president began the substantive part of his speech with the paradoxes that would characterize it as a whole. â€œMan holds in his mortal hands the power to abolish all forms of human poverty and all forms of human life,â€ he said, referring to what he saw as the responsibility of the industrialized nations to help developing nations and the superpowers to rid the world of nuclear weapon arsenals.</para>
<figure id="BRI_APUSH_14_03_KennedyIna" class="full-width">
<media id="fs-idm495327072" alt="President Kennedy stands behind a podium and delivers a speech from the balcony of the Capitol. A crowd sits behind him.">
<image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/BRI_APUSH_14_03_KennedyIna.jpg"/>
</media>
<caption>President Kennedy braved the freezing temperatures during his inaugural address with no hat or overcoat. (credit: U.S. Army Signal Corps photograph in the John F. Kennedy Presidential Library and Museum, Boston)</caption>
</figure>
<para id="fs-idm464355424">The speech committed the United States to the defense of freedom during the Cold War. After his first point, Kennedy spoke a line that soon became famous: â€œLet the word go forth to friend and foe alike, that a torch has been passed to a new generation of Americans.â€ Kennedy was the first president born after 1900 and was part of the â€œGreatest Generation,â€ forged in the challenges of the Great Depression and World War II. After he briefly expanded on this idea, he made his signature remark announcing an expansive foreign policy goal of defending global freedom: â€œLet every nation know, whether it wishes us well or ill, that we shall pay any price, bear any burden, meet any hardship, support any friend, oppose any foe to assure the survival and the success of liberty.â€ When the Vietnam War intensified after Kennedyâ€™s death, criticism of this line arose, implicating it in fostering ill-advised military intervention in Vietnam. The inaugural did not render itself immune from such criticisms; its next line was, â€œThis much we pledgeâ€”and more.â€</para>
<para id="fs-idm376944448">Kennedy mentioned communism explicitly in the address, in a section concerning the poorer â€œhalf [of] the globeâ€ (the â€œThird World,â€ a term that had arisen in the 1950s), saying that, â€œTo those peoples, we pledge our best efforts to help them help themselves,â€¦not because the communists may be doing it,â€¦but because it is right.â€ This point was emphasized later in the speech, with Kennedy stating, â€œIf a free society cannot help the many who are poor, it cannot save the few who are rich.â€ President Kennedy fulfilled this part of his vision by working with Congress to establish the Peace Corps, the Alliance for Progress (for Latin America), and the Agency for International Development to promote economic growth in developing nations.</para>
<para id="fs-idm359147376">Alluding to the Cold War struggle against the Soviet Union, Kennedy addressed those communist nations, led by the Soviet Union, that together stood as an â€œadversaryâ€ of the United States. He affirmed that the United States would maintain a strong defense even as it acknowledged the incomparable danger of nuclear annihilation. Therefore, he raised the prospect of sincere and earnest negotiations between the superpowers. He mused that â€œnot all this will be finished in the firstâ€¦.one thousand days, nor will [this work] be finishedâ€¦perhaps in our lifetime on this planet.â€ But he pledged he would be willing to begin the process with the Soviet Union.</para>
<para id="fs-idm463186704">Kennedy closed the speech with a call to public service and sacrifice even amid postwar plenty. He issued a â€œtrumpet summonsâ€¦. not as a call to battle, though embattled we are.â€ Being â€œembattledâ€ referred to the preparedness of the American people to defend themselves whatever the potential cost to their burgeoning prosperity. Kennedyâ€™s call was one of responsibility, as a global and strategic superpower, to serve other nations and the cause of peace. He said he did not think Americans would shirk their responsibilities regardless of the difficulties. â€œI do not believe that any of us would exchange places with any other people or any other generation.â€ He finished the speech by asking Americans to face the daunting tasks ahead. â€œAnd so, my fellow Americans: ask not what your country can do for youâ€”ask what you can do for your country.â€ Echoing Lincoln at Gettysburg and perhaps inadvertently Frost in â€œThe Gift Outright,â€ he closed with a call to â€œgo forth to lead the land we love,â€ before invoking â€œGodâ€™s blessing.â€</para>
<para id="fs-idm383355968">Ten days later, Kennedy gave his first State of the Union message. It was a long and detailed policy program, much of it having to do with domestic spending. In this way, it was complementary to the inaugural, whose large thoughts and interesting turns of phrase now were accompanied by the elucidation of practical details. How much the thousand days of the Kennedy presidency may have flowed from the impulses of the inaugural remains a difficult question. During his administration, Kennedy affirmed U.S. commitments in Latin America, began the tradition of signing arms limitation treaties with the Soviet Union, and started the Peace Corps, all as generally suggested in the address. But he also grew in his office and met challenges with solutions not contained in the inaugural address. His two major legislative accomplishmentsâ€”the civil rights and tax cut bills introduced in 1963 and made law in 1964â€”remain hard to connect to the themes to which he had dedicated himself in the speech.</para>
